article.headline: New Mexico State 69, UC Irvine 64
article.story: LAS CRUCES, N.M. (AP) -- Allen Haynes is no longer in a shooting slump and it couldn't happen at a better time for New Mexico State. The former Hobbs High School star scored 22 points and tied his career high with seven 3-pointers Saturday to lead the Aggies to a 69-64 win over UC-Irvine. "I felt like I couldn't miss," Haynes said of his 7-for-10 proficiency from behind the 3-point arc. "It felt good to finally make some shots." Haynes has averaged 6.8 points a game and has hit just 37 percent of his shots this season. But he's had three straight double-figure scoring games, with 10 points against Louisiana-Lafayette and 11 against South Alabama. The non-conference win got the Aggies to .500 (12-12) and gave 72-year-old coach Lou Henson his 774th career win. He ranks seventh all-time in Division I. The Aggies are trying to qualify for the Sun Belt Conference tournament. Eight teams will play in the tournament and New Mexico State currently is tied with Denver for the final spot. The Aggies play at Denver on Monday, then finish up the regular season with two home games next week. If Haynes continues to score the way he did Saturday, the Aggies' chances of making the Sun Belt tournament field should improve. Defense hasn't been the problem, since NMSU leads the conference in scoring defense, giving up just 65 points a game -- the best scoring defense the Aggies have had in 17 years. "We came out and played really well in the second half," New Mexico State coach Lou Henson said. "Now, we just have to try and carry over the momentum to our remaining conference games." NMSU scored six straight points to take a 67-61 lead with 50 seconds left. UC Irvine's Ross Schraeder hit a 3-pointer with nine seconds remaining, but the Aggies iced the win on two free throws by Gary Jackson with four seconds left. Adam Parada led the Anteaters (10-14) with 23 points and six rebounds. Stanislav Zuzak added 16 points. Parada hit 8 of his 10 shots and was 7-for-8 at the free throw line. Duane John and James Moore each scored 11 points for the Aggies. Moore also had four blocks to run his total for the season to 50. The Anteaters scored the game's first 10 points, with a Haynes 3-pointer giving the Aggies their first points nearly four minutes into the game. UC Irvine led 35-32 at halftime, but New Mexico State took advantage of a six-minute scoring drought by the Anteaters midway through the second half to score 12 straight points. A free throw by Moore with 6:26 left gave the Aggies their first lead of the game (56-55) and a 3-pointer by Haynes finished the run and put NMSU in front 61-55. UC Irvine scored the next six points on free throws by Parada and Zuzak and a layup by Jeff Gloger to tie it at 61 with 3:53 left.
